9:00:00','2019-04-01 22:00:00','Evergrey\nSince 1993, the Swedish group surrounding frontman/songwriter Tom S. Englund has been synonymous with technically and compositionally outstanding standards, combined with lyrics and messages which go way beyond pure rock‚Äôn‚Äôroll prose. For The Broken trilogy about the adventure of life, part one having been launched in 2014. \nEvergrey take their fans on a tempestuous expedition across the rough (prog metal) seas. \n\n\nThe album kicks off with ‚ÄòA Silent Arc‚Äô, one of the probably fiercest and toughest numbers that Evergrey have ever recorded. ‚ÄúI love this song,‚Äù confesses Englund. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs really brutal in a certain kind of Evergrey way, with guitars that you might expect from a band like Behemoth, but certainly not from us. We‚Äôve never sounded as dark or as raw before.‚Äù At the same time, ‚ÄòA Silent Arc‚Äô focuses the whole musical and lyrical content of The Atlantic. So wouldn‚Äôt it suggest itself to present the song ‚Äì which will also be the first single release ‚Äì in an atmospheric video clip? ‚ÄúWell,‚Äù says Englund, ‚Äúthis time we‚Äôd want our listeners to create their own images when listening to this song and let them indulge in their own movie in front of their inner eye, at least at first‚Äù There will, however, be videos to support the atmospherically heavy ‚ÄòWeightless‚Äô and the anthemnic ‚ÄòAll I Have‚Äô, both diverse highlights of a thoroughly haunting album which was mixed and mastered by Jacob Hansen. ‚ÄúAs with every album, we‚Äôve given this one our all to come up with the optimum result,‚Äù enthuses Englund, who produced The Atlantic together with drummer Jonas Ekdahl, about the driving sound. The ten songs on the album all stand out with their amazing power, but also with their depth and exciting detail. ‚ÄòDeparture‚Äô, for example, embeds its vocals mainly in bass, drums, piano and acoustic guitar. ‚ÄúThat kind of song writing is something we‚Äôve enjoyed doing on every album of this trilogy,‚Äù Englund explains proudly, adding: ‚ÄúThis number sounds like an expedition instead of being arranged like your typical three-and-a-half minute hit.‚Äù Which applies to The Atlantic in general. Englund: ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs probably our most complex and progressive release so far and includes all the elements that our fans love.‚Äù One thing is clear: musical fast food sounds different ‚Äì Evergrey serve exquisite wholefood cuisine.\n\n\n\n\n+ Bloodred Hourglass\nBloodred Hourglass, known as BRHG, is a Melodic Death Metal band from Mikkeli, Finland. The history of the project roots back to 2005, when the first self-made demo was scratched together. The first full length studio album \"Lifebound\" was released in 2012 and three years later it was time for the second one: \"Where The Oceans Burn\" was out in October 2015. In January 2017 BRHG finished the recordings of their next album titled \"Heal\" that was released in Finland on October 2017 via Ranka Kustannus, claiming #13 on the official Finnish Album Chart. \n\nThe album was later also released in Japan on December via Ward Records as well as in central Europe through Out Of Line Music in January 2018. Bloodred Hourglass combines elements and influences from various different musical genres with main focus on Metal. Fast drum patterns, thrashy riffage among big guitar walls, a lot of melodic atmosphere due to keyboards together with growling and screaming aggressive vocals are the main architects behind the sound of this five man band. Despite the variety of influences and different type of elements you can hear in our material, we feel our music is closest to be described as Melodic Death Metal. Lyrical themes are focused on individuals experience of everyday life, as well as aspects of environmental issues.',NULL,0,0,NULL,'\"{\\\"invited\\\": null, \\\"attending\\\": 55}\"','a4b96270-6e1a-43a2-afeb-a9922c7f0938','285283785493745',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2019-02-19 21:34:00','2019-11-06 22:10:29'),(187,21,'S